 Variable: variable used to stored values to achieve the project requirement.
Types of variables:
	1) Local variable.
	2) Instance variable.
	3) Static variable.
	
Class Test\
{	variables
	method 
	constructors
	instance block 
	static block
	
}
Local variable:
==============
1) variable which is declared inside the method or constructors or blocks is called local variable.
2) scope: inside the  method /constructors we can use the local variable.
3) Memory: local variable memory is allocated when method start & memory released when the method is completed.
4) Local variable stored in stack memory.
	void m1 () // memory  allocated 
	{
		int a =6; //local variable 
		System.out.println(a); // possible 
	}	memory  released 
	void m2 ()
	{
	System.out.println(a); // not possible
	}
	
..................................................................
Instance variable.
================
1) variable which is declared inside the class but out side the method is called Instance variable.
2) scope: inside the class all method,constructor and instance /static blocks able to access the instance variable.
3) Memory: Instance variable memory is allocated when object is created & memory released when object is destroyed.
4) Instance variable stored in heap memory.

public class InstanceVariable {
	
	int a=10; //instance variable
	int b=20;
	int c=30;
	public static void main(String[] args) { 
		// static area so we need to create object then use the instance variable
		// execution will start from main method
		InstanceVariable t= new InstanceVariable();
		System.out.println(t.a);
		System.out.println(t.b);
		t.m1();	
	}
	void m1() // instance method we can use the instance variable directly 
	{
	System.out.println(c);
	}
}
........................................................................

Static variable
----------------
1. a variable which is declared inside the class but out side the method with static modifier is called Instance variable.
2. Static variable memory is allocated at the time of class loading.
3. Scope: In the class.
4. Static variable stored in non Heap memory.

class staticvariable1 
{
	static int a=10;
	static int b=20; //static variables 
	void m1() // instance method 
	{
		System.out.println(staticvariable1.a);
	}
	public static void main(String[] args) 
	{
		staticvariable1 t = new staticvariable1();
		t.m1();
		System.out.println(staticvariable1.a);
		System.out.println(staticvariable1.b);
	}
}
-----------
assignment1 
-----------
class assignment1
{
	int a=10; // instance variable
	int b=20;
	static void m1() // static method
	{
		assignment1 t= new assignment1();
		System.out.println(t.a);
		System.out.println(t.b);
	}
	static void m2() // static method
	{
		assignment1 t= new assignment1();
		System.out.println(t.a);
		System.out.println(t.b);
	}

	public static void main (String [] arg)
	{
	assignment1 t= new assignment1();
	t.m1();
	t.m2();
	}
}
-----------
assignment2
-----------
class assignment2
{

	int a =10;
	int b=20;
	static int c=30;
	static int d=40;
	void m1()
	{
		System.out.println(a);
		System.out.println(b);
		assignment2 t= new assignment2();
		System.out.println(t.c);
		System.out.println(t.d);
	}
	static void m2()
	{
		assignment2 t = new assignment2();
		System.out.println(t.a);
		System.out.println(t.b);
		System.out.println(assignment2.c);
		System.out.println(assignment2.d);
	}
public static void main (String [] arg)
	{
		assignment2 t=new assignment2();
		t.m1();
		t.m2();

	}
}

=========================
CLASS VS OBJECT 
1. Class is is a logical entity contains logic of application. object is physical entity represent the memory.
2. Class is a blue print document that decide the object creation. 
3. single blue print class having  -> multiple object use memory  
4.  Declareation using Class keyword - new keyword.

